In LaTeX, the table of contents (TOC) can be automatically generated by using the `\tableofcontents` command. This command processes all sectioning commands in your document (such as `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) to create the TOC.

Here's an example of how you can generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents    % This is where the table of contents will appear
\newpage            % Start the content on a new page after the TOC

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction of the document.

\subsection{Background}
This subsection provides background information.

\subsection{Scope}
This subsection discusses the scope of the document.

\section{Methodology}
The methodology section explains the approach taken in the document.

\subsection{Data Collection}
This subsection details how data was collected.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
This subsection describes the analysis of the data.

\section{Results}
Here the results are presented.

\section{Conclusion}
This section contains the concluding remarks.

\end{document}
```

When you compile this LaTeX document, the `\tableofcontents` command will work with the `\section` and `\subsection` commands to create an appropriately formatted table of contents. Remember that you may need to compile the document twice to get the table of contents fully updated, especially if you make any changes that would affect the numbering or titles of sections.

